         <abstract>
            <p>The following theorem is proved in this paper: "If the first case of Fermat's Last Theorem does not hold for sufficiently large prime l, then &lt;latex&gt;$\sum_x^{l - 2} \bigg\lbrack \frac{kl}{N} &lt; x &lt; \frac{(k + 1)l}{N}\bigg\rbrack \equiv 0\quad(\operatorname{mod} l)$&lt;/latex&gt; for all pairs of positive integers N, k, N ≤ 94, 0 ≤ k ≤ N - 1." The proof of this theorem is based on a recent paper of Skula and uses computer techniques.</p>
          </abstract>
